class LogisticRegression(object):
    def __init__(self, alpha=0., method='L-BFGS-B', tol=None):
        '''
        
        Parameters
        ----------
        
        :method: 'CG', 'L-BFGS-B', ..
        :alpha: Corresponds to the regularization parameter lambda
        '''
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.method = method
        self.tol = tol
        self.coef_ = []

    def fit(self, X, y, silent=False):        
        # init coefs
        if (len(self.coef_) != X.shape[1] + 1):
            self.coef_ = [0]*(X.shape[1] + 1)
            
        X_with_bias = LogisticRegression.add_bias(X)
        self.cost_function_values = []
        #if (verbose):
        if (silent == False):
            print('start fitting,\n\tshape X:', X_with_bias.shape, 
                  '\n\tshape y:', y.shape, 
                  '\n\t#coefs:', len(self.coef_), 
                  '\n\tregul_alpha:', self.alpha)
        
        res = minimize(self.cost_function, 
                       x0=self.coef_,
                       args=(X_with_bias, y, self.alpha, self.cost_function_values),
                       method=self.method, 
                       jac=self.gradient, 
                       tol=self.tol,
                       )
        self.coef_ = res.x
        if (silent == False):
            print('done fitting, length grad:', np.linalg.norm(self.gradient(self.coef_, X_with_bias, y, self.alpha, None)), 
                  '\n\tlast cost function value:',self.cost_function(self.coef_,X_with_bias,y,self.alpha,None),
                  '\n\t#steps',res.nit,
                  '\n\tsuccess:', res.success,
                  '\n\tmessage:', res.message)
        
        return res
    
    @staticmethod
    def sigmoid(x):
        x[x<-100]=-100
        x[x>100]=100
        
        return 1/(1+np.exp(-x))
        
    @staticmethod
    def cost_function(beta, X, y, alpha, cost_function_values = None):
        calcBeta = np.reshape(beta, (X.shape[1],1))
        
        phi = LogisticRegression.sigmoid(X.dot(calcBeta))
        phi_correct_epsilon = 10**-15
        phi[phi == 0] = phi_correct_epsilon
        phi[phi == 1] = 1-phi_correct_epsilon
        first_part = -y*np.log(phi) - (1-y)*np.log(1-phi)
        first_part = first_part.sum()
          
        if (alpha != 0):
            first_part += (alpha) * (beta[1:]**2).sum()
        
        if (cost_function_values is not None):
            cost_function_values.append(first_part)
            
        return first_part

    @staticmethod
    def gradient(beta, X, y, alpha, cost_function_values = None):
        calcBeta = np.reshape(beta, (X.shape[1],1))
        first_part = (LogisticRegression.sigmoid(np.dot(X,calcBeta)) - y)*X
        first_part = first_part.sum(axis=0)
        regul = 0
        if (alpha != 0):
            regul = (2* alpha*beta[1:]).sum()
        gradupdate = first_part + regul
        return LogisticRegression.unroll(gradupdate)
    
    def predict(self, X):
        workingX = X
        if (X.shape[1] != len(self.coef_)):
            workingX = LogisticRegression.add_bias(X)
        return workingX.dot(self.coef_) >= 0.5
    
    def score(self, X, y, method='accuracy', verbose=False):       
        yPredicted = self.predict(self.add_bias(X))
        yBool = y.astype(bool)
        yPredictedBool = yPredicted.astype(bool)
        TP = np.logical_and(yBool, yPredictedBool).sum()
        FP = np.logical_and(yBool == False, yPredictedBool).sum()
        
        TN = np.logical_and(yBool == False, yPredictedBool == False).sum()
        FN = np.logical_and(yBool, yPredictedBool == False).sum()
        
        PredictedT = yPredictedBool.sum()
        PredictedN = (yPredictedBool == False).sum()
        
        SampleT = yBool.sum()
        SampleN = (yBool == False).sum()
        
        Total = y.shape[0]
        if (verbose):
            print('TP: {TP}, FP: {FP}, TN: {TN}, FN: {FN}'.format(TP=TP, FP=FP, TN=TN, FN=FN))
        
        if (method == 'accuracy'):
            return (TP + TN)/Total
        if (method == 'precision'):
            return TP / PredictedT
        if (method == 'recall'):
            return TP / SampleT
        if (method == 'f1'):
            prec = (TP / PredictedT)
            rec = (TP / SampleT)
            return 2*(prec * rec) / (prec + rec)
    
    @staticmethod
    def add_bias(X):
        return np.column_stack((np.ones(X.shape[0]),X))
        #return np.insert(X, 0, 1., axis=1)
            
        
    def print_learningCurve(self):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
        _ = ax.plot(self.cost_function_values, label='cost function Werte');
        _ = ax.set_ylabel(r'J($\beta$)')
        _ = ax.set_xlabel('Anzahl Schritte')
        _ = ax.set_title('Lern-Kurve')
        _ = ax.legend()
        return fig, ax
      
    @staticmethod
    def unroll(X):
        flatted = []
        for w in X:
            flatted.append(w.flatten())
        return np.concatenate(flatted);
    
        
    def confusion_matrix(self, X,y):
        predicted = self.predict(X).astype(int)
        real_y = np.atleast_2d(y.copy()).astype(int)
        if (real_y.shape[1] == 1):
            newFCol = []
            for newF in real_y:
                newFCol.append((newF == 0))
            real_y = np.column_stack((np.array(newFCol), real_y))
            newFCol = []
            for newF in predicted:
                newFCol.append((newF == 0))
            
            predicted = np.column_stack(( np.array(newFCol), predicted))
        n_classes = real_y.shape[1]
        c_matrix = np.zeros((n_classes,n_classes))            
        
        for idx, ry in enumerate(real_y):
            c_matrix[np.argmax(predicted[idx])][np.argmax(ry)] += 1
        return c_matrix
        
    @staticmethod
    def plot_confusion_as_table(co_matrix):
        #plt.figure()
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
        #ax = plt.subplot(111, frame_on=False) 
        ax.xaxis.set_visible(False) 
        ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
        tb = ax.table(cellText=co_matrix, 
               loc='center', 
               cellLoc='center',
               rowLoc='center',
               rowLabels=range(co_matrix.shape[0]), 
               colLabels=range(co_matrix.shape[1]))
        tb.set_fontsize(30)
        tb.scale(1,4)
        ax.set_title('confusion matrix')
        return fig, ax, tb

def plot_decision_regions(X, y, classifier, resolution=0.02, x_label = '', y_label='', title = ''):
    markers = ('o', 'o', 'o', 'o', 'o')
    colors = ('red', 'blue', 'lightgreen', 'gray', 'cyan')
    cmap = ListedColormap(colors[:len(np.unique(y))])
    
    # plot the decision surface
    x1_min, x1_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    x2_min, x2_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x1_min, x1_max, resolution),
    np.arange(x2_min, x2_max, resolution))
    Z = classifier.predict(np.array([xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()]).T)
    Z = Z.reshape(xx1.shape)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,6))
    contour = ax.contourf(xx1, xx2, Z, alpha=0.4, cmap=cmap)
    ax.set_xlim(xx1.min(), xx1.max())
    ax.set_ylim(xx2.min(), xx2.max())
    
    y = np.array(y.flatten())

    # plot all samples
    for idx, cl in enumerate(np.unique(y)):
        ax.scatter(x=X[y == cl, 0], y=X[y == cl, 1],
        alpha=0.8, c=cmap(idx),
        marker=markers[idx], label=cl,
        edgecolor='none')
    _ = ax.set_xlabel(x_label)
    _ = ax.set_ylabel(y_label)
    _ = ax.set_title(title)
    
def plot_decision_regions_poly(X, y, classifier, resolution=0.02, x_label = '', y_label='', title = '', degree = 1):
    markers = ('o', 'o', 'o', 'o', 'o')
    colors = ('red', 'blue', 'lightgreen', 'gray', 'cyan')
    cmap = ListedColormap(colors[:len(np.unique(y))])
    
    # plot the decision surface
    x1_min, x1_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    x2_min, x2_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x1_min, x1_max, resolution),
    np.arange(x2_min, x2_max, resolution))
    xx1R = xx1.ravel()
    xx2R = xx2.ravel()
    xxR = np.array([xx1R, xx2R])

    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree).fit_transform(xxR.T)
    Z = classifier.predict(poly)
    # print(Z.shape)
    # print(xx1.shape)
    Z = Z.reshape(xx1.shape)
    # print(Z.shape)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,6))
    contour = ax.contourf(xx1, xx2, Z, alpha=0.4, cmap=cmap)
    ax.set_xlim(xx1.min(), xx1.max())
    ax.set_ylim(xx2.min(), xx2.max())
    
    y = np.array(y.flatten())
    
    # plot all samples
    for idx, cl in enumerate(np.unique(y)):
        ax.scatter(x=X[y == cl, 0], y=X[y == cl, 1],
        alpha=0.8, c=cmap(idx),
        marker=markers[idx], label=cl,
        edgecolor='none')
    _ = ax.set_xlabel(x_label)
    _ = ax.set_ylabel(y_label)
    _ = ax.set_title(title)
    
    
def draw_histogram(data, title, dataLabel='Histogram', printMeanLine=True, printStdLines=True, printMedian=True, bins = 40):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 5))

    _ = ax.hist(data, bins=bins, label=dataLabel)
    
    
    mean = data.mean()
    if (printMeanLine):
        _ = ax.axvline(mean, color='y', linewidth=2, label='Durchscnitt {mean}'.format(mean=mean))   
    if (printMedian):
        median = np.median(data)
        _ = ax.axvline(median, color='c',linewidth=2,label='Median: {median}'.format(median=median))
    if (printStdLines):
        std = data.std()
        _ = ax.axvline(mean-std, color='r', linewidth=2, label='Durchschnitt-std')
        _ = ax.axvline(mean+std, color='r', linewidth=2, label='Durchschnitt+std')
         
    
    _ = ax.set_xlabel(dataLabel)
    _ = ax.set_ylabel('Anzahl')
    _ = ax.set_title(title)
    _ = ax.legend()
    return fig, ax;


def print_scores(log_reg, x, y, title = ''):
    print(title,'\n\tPrecision:\t{prec}\n\tRecall:\t\t{rec}\n\tF1-Score:\t{f1}\n\tAccuracy:\t{acc}'
          .format(prec=log_reg.score(x, y, method='precision'), 
                  rec=log_reg.score(x, y, method='recall'),
                  f1=log_reg.score(x, y, method='f1'),
                  acc=log_reg.score(x, y, method='accuracy')))

def lr_poly_wo_regul():
    print('++++++++++++++++++++ poly overfitting ++++++++++++++++++++')
    degree = 5
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree).fit_transform(devX)
    
    lr_poly = LogisticRegression(tol=10**-5, alpha=0.0)

    plot_decision_regions_poly(devX, devy, lr_poly, degree=degree, title='poly overfitting', x_label='X0', y_label='X1')

    sy = np.array(devy.flatten())
    print_scores(lr_poly, poly, sy, 'scores poly overfitting:')
    print('-------------------- poly --------------------')

Interpretation¶

dev1¶

Beim ersten Plot sieht man auf der X achse die X0 werte und auf der Y achse die X1 werte. Colorcoded sind die y-Werte dargestellt. Bei der Lernkurve sieht man auf der X-Achse die Anzahl Schritte gegenber auf der Y-Achse die Werte der Cost-function (J($\beta$))

Man sieht auf der Lernkurve, dass das Modell ohne Regularisierung konvertiert. Auf dem decision region plot sieht man die linie da wo ich sie erwarte, sie trennt die Daten in ungefhr gleich grosse Teile und ist nicht gekrmmt.

poly overfitting¶

Die Plots zeigen auf der X & Y Achse dieselben Daten wie vorher.

Der Unterschied ist, dass hier die Features polynomial erweitert wurden (grad = 5) Hier sieht man gut, ohne Regularisierung wird ein extremes overfitting betrieben. Alle scores sind natrlich bei 1.0 Auch dieser Plot entspricht meinen Erwartungen.

poly regularisiert¶

Die Plots zeigen auf der X & Y Achse dieselben Daten wie vorher.

Hier sieht man, dass die Regularisierung funktioniert, die scores sind besser als ohne poly, schlechter als die mit overfitting. Allerdings ist hier weniger overfitting vorhanden. Man sieht, dass die linie die daten fast optimal trennt.

def prepareData(cols, addZip = False, addViewOhe = False):
    trainX = np.array(df[cols]).astype(float)
    testX = np.array(df_test[cols]).astype(float)
    
    xScaler = StandardScaler()
    trainX = xScaler.fit_transform(trainX)
    testX = xScaler.transform(testX)

    if (addZip):
        #zip code ohe
        ohe = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False)
        zipcode = ohe.fit_transform(np.atleast_2d(np.array(df['zipcode'])).T)
        zipcode_test = ohe.transform(np.atleast_2d(np.array(df_test['zipcode'])).T)

        trainX = np.hstack((trainX, zipcode))
        testX = np.hstack((testX, zipcode_test))
        
    if (addViewOhe):
        ohe = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False)
        view = ohe.fit_transform(np.atleast_2d(np.array(df['view'])).T)
        view_test = ohe.transform(np.atleast_2d(np.array(df_test['view'])).T)

        trainX = np.hstack((trainX, view))
        testX = np.hstack((testX, view_test))
    return trainX, testX

def oversample_lr():
    # find # of data to use class:
    n_data = trainy_lr.shape[0] - int(trainy_lr.sum(axis=0))
    
    trainX_lr4 = None
    trainy_lr4 = None
    n_expected = 0
    
    n_samples = int(trainy_lr.sum(axis=0))

    n_duplicates = int(n_data/n_samples)
    n_expected = n_duplicates * n_samples + n_data
    print('ns: ', n_samples, 'ndup', n_duplicates, 'ndata', n_data)
    for idx, cv in enumerate(trainy_lr):
        #add to train set
        if (trainX_lr4 is None):
            trainX_lr4 = np.array(trainX_lr3[idx])
            trainy_lr4 = np.array(trainy_lr[idx])
        else:
            trainX_lr4 = np.vstack((trainX_lr4, trainX_lr3[idx]))
            trainy_lr4 = np.vstack((trainy_lr4, trainy_lr[idx]))
        #duplicate if in minority class
        if (cv == 1):
            for z in range(n_duplicates - 1):
                trainX_lr4 = np.vstack((trainX_lr4, trainX_lr3[idx]))
                trainy_lr4 = np.vstack((trainy_lr4, trainy_lr[idx]))

    print('length should be #class * n_data (with a bit of arounding margin)\nexpected: {e}\ngot:{r}'.format(e=n_expected, r=trainy_lr4.shape[0]))
    return trainX_lr4, trainy_lr4

Schlusswort Logistische Regression¶

Die 3 Modelle verfolgen unterschiedliche Ziele, so ist beispielsweise das Modell 1 & 2 dazu da, den Einfluss von Zip zu prfen. Das 3. Modell versucht einen mglichst hohen Recall zu erreichen. # Implementation Algorithm
# ungleichgewicht beheben & effekt betrachten.
# verschiedene Metriken
# unbalanced dataset classification / Metrik
# https://machinelearningmastery.com/tactics-to-combat-imbalanced-classes-in-your-machine-learning-dataset/

class MultiLayerPerceptron:
    def __init__(self, units = [], reg_lambda = 5, method='L-BFGS-B', tol=10**-8, maxiter = 10**5, correct_misfit = True):
        self.units = units
        self.reg_lambda = reg_lambda
        self.layers = len(units)
        self.method = method
        self.tol = tol
        self.maxiter = maxiter
        self.correct_misfit = correct_misfit
        self.cost_function_values = []
        self.score_values = []
        self.cost_function_values_step = []
        
        # weight random initialisation
        rand_eps = 0.7
        self.weights = []
        self.shapes = []
        for l in range(1, len(units)):
            randWeights = 2*rand_eps*np.random.rand(units[l],units[l-1] + 1) - rand_eps
            self.weights.append(randWeights)
            self.shapes.append(randWeights.shape)
        
    def setWeights(self, weights):
        self.weights = weights
    
    def fit(self, X, y, verbose=False, method='minimize', batchsize=1, learning_rate = 10**-5, print_gen_update=True, silent=False):
        self.cost_function_values =[]
        self.cost_function_values_step =[]
        if (silent == False):
            print('start fitting:\n\tshape X:', X.shape,
                  '\n\tshape y:', y.shape, 
                  '\n\tunits:', self.units,
                  '\n\treg_lambda:', self.reg_lambda,
                  '\n\ttol:', self.tol,
                  '\n\tmaxstep:', self.maxiter,
                  '\n\tcorrect misfits:',self.correct_misfit,
                  '\n\tbatchsize:',batchsize)
            
        #stocastic gradient decent
        if (method == 'sgd'):
            res = self.fit_batching(X, y, 1, learning_rate, verbose, print_gen_update)
            self.weights = self.uproll(res, self.shapes)
            
        if (method == 'batch'):
            res = self.fit_batching(X, y, batchsize, learning_rate, verbose, print_gen_update)
            self.weights = self.uproll(res, self.shapes)
            
        if (method=='minimize'):
            unrolledWeights = self.unroll(self.weights)
            res = minimize(self.cost_function,
                     x0=unrolledWeights,
                     args=(X, y, self.reg_lambda, self.shapes, self.layers, self.cost_function_values),
                     jac=self.back_propag,
                     method=self.method, 
                     tol=self.tol,
                     options={'maxiter':self.maxiter,'disp':True}
                    )
            if (verbose):
                print('success: ', res.success)
                print('message: ', res.message)

            self.weights = self.uproll(res.x, self.shapes)
            if (silent == False):
                print('done fitting, length grad:',
                      np.linalg.norm(self.back_propag(res.x, X, y, self.reg_lambda, self.shapes, self.layers, None)),
                      '\n\tlast cost function value:',
                      self.cost_function(res.x, X, y, self.reg_lambda, self.shapes, self.layers, None),
                      '\n\t#steps', res.nit,
                      '\n\tsuccess:', res.success,
                      '\n\tmessage:', res.message)
        
        
        
    def fit_batching(self, X, y, batchsize, learning_rate = 10**-5, verbose = False, print_gen_update=True):
        numberOfData = X.shape[0] 
        epochLength = math.ceil(numberOfData / batchsize)
        
        epochCounter = 0
        unrolledWeights = MultiLayerPerceptron.unroll(self.weights)
        stepsize = 1
        canStop = False
        lastWeights = unrolledWeights.copy()
        lastCFV = MultiLayerPerceptron.cost_function(unrolledWeights, X, y, reg_lambda=self.reg_lambda, shapes=self.shapes, layers =self.layers, cost_function_values = self.cost_function_values, verbose=False)
        while ((epochCounter < self.maxiter) and (not canStop)):
            permutatedIndexes = np.random.permutation(numberOfData)
            
            for i in range(epochLength):
                batchIndex = permutatedIndexes[i*batchsize: (i+1)*batchsize]
                batchX = X[batchIndex]
                batchY = y[batchIndex]
                self.cost_function_values_step.append(self.cost_function(unrolledWeights, batchX, batchY, reg_lambda=self.reg_lambda, shapes=self.shapes, layers=self.layers, cost_function_values=None, verbose=False))
                neg_grad = -self.back_propag(unrolledWeights, batchX, batchY, reg_lambda=self.reg_lambda, shapes=self.shapes, layers=self.layers, cost_function_values=self.cost_function_values, verbose=False)
                stepsize /= 1+learning_rate*(i+(epochCounter*epochLength))
                unrolledWeights += stepsize * neg_grad
                if (verbose):
                    print('curr stepsize', stepsize)
                if ((stepsize == 0) or (math.isnan(stepsize))):
                    print('error, stepsize to small')
                    return
            epochCounter += 1
            # appends cost function values
            cfv = MultiLayerPerceptron.cost_function(unrolledWeights, X, y, reg_lambda=self.reg_lambda, shapes=self.shapes, layers =self.layers, cost_function_values = self.cost_function_values, verbose=False)
            if (print_gen_update):
                print('done fitting epoche ', epochCounter)
                uprolled = MultiLayerPerceptron.uproll(unrolledWeights, self.shapes)
                gen_score = self.static_score(X,y,weights=uprolled, layers=self.layers)
                print('score for this epoche: ', gen_score)
                self.score_values.append(gen_score)
                print('cost_function for this epoche: ', cfv)
            if ((self.correct_misfit) and (lastCFV < cfv)):
                #misfit in this generation
                canStop = False
                unrolledWeights = lastWeights
            else:
                canStop = abs(lastCFV - cfv) <= self.tol
                lastCFV = cfv
                lastWeights = unrolledWeights
        
        message = ''
        success = (epochCounter < self.maxiter)
        if (success):
            message = 'J()_n - J()_{n-1} < tol'
        else:
            message = 'maxiter'
        print('done fitting, length grad:',
              np.linalg.norm(self.back_propag(unrolledWeights, X, y, self.reg_lambda,self.shapes,self.layers,None)),
              '\n\tlast cost function value:',
              self.cost_function(unrolledWeights, X, y, self.reg_lambda,self.shapes,self.layers,None),
              '\n\t#epochs', epochCounter,
              ' => #steps = ',epochCounter*epochLength,
              '\n\tsuccess:', success,
              '\n\tmessage:', message)
        
        #print('done fitting generations after ', epochCounter, 'epochs')
        return unrolledWeights
            
    @staticmethod
    def cost_function(weights, X, y, reg_lambda=None, shapes=None, layers = None, cost_function_values = None, verbose=False):
        n = X.shape[0];
        k = np.atleast_2d(y).shape[1];
        cf_sum = 0;
        
        weights = MultiLayerPerceptron.uproll(weights, shapes)          
        predicted = MultiLayerPerceptron.a(layer=layers, weights=weights, X=X)
        for l in range(k):
            pred = predicted[l]
            y_l = y.T[l]   
            phi_correct_epsilon = 10**-15
            pred[pred == 0] = phi_correct_epsilon
            pred[pred == 1] = 1-phi_correct_epsilon
            cf_sum += (y_l*np.log(pred) + (1-y_l)*np.log(1-pred)).sum()
        
        if (verbose):
            print ('cf_sum:', cf_sum)
        cf_sum = cf_sum / -n
        
        regul  = 0;
        for wl in weights:
            if (verbose):
                print('w shape:', wl.shape)
            
            weight_without_bias = wl.T[1:]
            if (verbose):
                print('w wo shape:', weight_without_bias.shape)
            regul += (weight_without_bias**2).sum()
        
        if (verbose):
            print('regul_sum', regul)
        regul = (reg_lambda * regul / (2*n))
        #regul = (reg_lambda * regul / (2))
        cfv = cf_sum + regul
        if (cost_function_values is not None):
            cost_function_values.append(cfv)
        return cfv
            
    def collect_cfv(self, cfv):
        self.cost_function_values.append(cfv)
    
        
    @staticmethod
    def a(layer = 1, weights = None, X = None, verbose=False):
        '''
        forward propagation calculation for layers
        '''
        if (verbose):
            print('calcing a for layer ',layer,'with x', X, weights)
        if (layer == 1):
            return X.T
            
        w = weights[layer-2]
        lastA = MultiLayerPerceptron.add_bias(MultiLayerPerceptron.a(layer-1, X=X, weights=weights, verbose=verbose)) 
        activatedResult= MultiLayerPerceptron.phi(w.dot(lastA))
        
        return activatedResult
    
    @staticmethod
    def calc_deltas(X,y,weights, layers, verbose = False):
        delta = [None]*(layers+1)       
        
        for l in reversed(range(2, layers + 1)):
            predicted = MultiLayerPerceptron.a(layer=l, X=X, weights=weights)
        
            if (l == layers):
                delta_l = predicted - y.T
            else:
                predicted = MultiLayerPerceptron.add_bias(predicted)
                theta_lT = weights[l-1].T
                if (verbose):
                    print('theta_{l}T {theta_l}'.format(l=l, theta_l=theta_lT))
                    print('multiply shape {s1} with {s2}'.format(s1 = theta_lT.shape, s2 = delta[l+1].shape))
                delta_l = theta_lT.dot(delta[l+1])*MultiLayerPerceptron.phiGrad(predicted)
                #remove bias
                delta_l = delta_l[1:len(delta_l)]
                
            delta[l] = delta_l
            if (verbose):
                print('delta_{l}'.format(l=l), delta_l)
        return delta
    
    @staticmethod
    def back_propag(weights, X, y, reg_lambda = None,shapes = None, layers = None, cost_function_values = None, verbose=False):
        uprolled = MultiLayerPerceptron.uproll(weights, shapes)
        Delta_grad = MultiLayerPerceptron.uproll(np.zeros(weights.shape), shapes)
        AllDeltas = MultiLayerPerceptron.calc_deltas(X=X, y=y, weights=uprolled, layers=layers, verbose=False)
        
        if (verbose):
            print('deltas:',AllDeltas)
            
        a_cache = [None]*(layers + 1)
        for l in range(1,len(a_cache)):
            a_cache[l] = (MultiLayerPerceptron.a(layer=l,X=X,weights=uprolled))
 
        if (verbose):
            print('------------------------------')
        for n, d_grad in enumerate(Delta_grad): 
            delta_l = n + 2
            a_l = n + 1

            if (verbose):
                print('----------',delta_l,'----------')

            aj = np.atleast_2d(MultiLayerPerceptron.add_bias(a_cache[a_l]))

            delta_i = np.atleast_2d(AllDeltas[delta_l]).T
            if (verbose):
                print('aj :{aj}, deltai={delta_i}'.format(aj=aj, delta_i=delta_i))
                print('shapes:',aj.shape,delta_i.shape)
                print('grad shape', d_grad.shape)

            gradUpdate = np.dot(aj,delta_i).T

            d_grad += gradUpdate
            if (verbose):
                print('grad update', gradUpdate)
                print('updated grad', d_grad)
        if (verbose):
            print('finished updating grad:')
            print(Delta_grad)
             
        numberOfData = X.shape[0]
        
        
        if (reg_lambda == 0):
            for d in Delta_grad:
                d /= numberOfData;
        else:
            for l in range(len(Delta_grad)):
                w = uprolled[l].T
                delta_grads = Delta_grad[l]
                w[0] = 0 # ignore bias for regul
                regulTherms = reg_lambda*w
                topPart = (delta_grads + regulTherms.T)
                
                Delta_grad[l] = topPart / numberOfData

        return MultiLayerPerceptron.unroll(Delta_grad)
    
    
    def check_grad_finite_diff(self, weights, X, y, reg_lambda = 0, grad_check_epsilon = 10**-3, verbose = False):
        unrolled = MultiLayerPerceptron.unroll(weights)
        aproxGrad = []
        
        for idx, t in enumerate(unrolled):
            copiedTPos = unrolled.copy()
            copiedTPos[idx] += grad_check_epsilon
            cfvPos = MultiLayerPerceptron.cost_function(copiedTPos, X, y, reg_lambda=reg_lambda, shapes=self.shapes, layers = self.layers, cost_function_values = None, verbose=False)
            
            copiedTNeg = unrolled.copy()
            copiedTNeg[idx] -= grad_check_epsilon
            cfvNeg = MultiLayerPerceptron.cost_function(copiedTNeg, X, y, reg_lambda=reg_lambda, shapes=self.shapes, layers = self.layers, cost_function_values = None, verbose=False)
            
            apr = (cfvPos - cfvNeg) / (2 * grad_check_epsilon)
            aproxGrad.append(apr)
            
        aproxGradV = np.linalg.norm(np.array(aproxGrad))
        
        calcGrad = MultiLayerPerceptron.back_propag(unrolled, X, y, reg_lambda = reg_lambda,shapes =self.shapes, layers =self.layers, cost_function_values = None, verbose=False)
        calcGradV = np.linalg.norm(calcGrad)
        if (verbose):
            print('are close:', np.isclose(aproxGrad, calcGrad))
            print('aprx:', np.array(aproxGrad))
            print('calc:',np.array(calcGrad))  
            print('aprxV:',aproxGradV)
            print('calcV:',calcGradV)
        
            print('summed', aproxGrad-calcGrad)
            
        print ('close: ', (np.isclose(aproxGrad, calcGrad).astype(int).sum() / len(aproxGrad)) * 100,'%')
    
    @staticmethod
    def add_bias(X):
        return np.insert(X, 0, 1., axis=0)

    @staticmethod
    def phi(x):
        x[x<-100]=-100
        x[x>100]=100
        return 1./(1+np.exp(-x))
    
    @staticmethod
    def phiGrad(x):
        return x*(1-x)
        
    @staticmethod
    def unroll(X):
        flatted = []
        for w in X:
            flatted.append(w.flatten())
        return np.concatenate(flatted);
    
    @staticmethod
    def uproll(X, shapes):
        retVal = []
        pointer = 0
        for shape in shapes:
            numberOfData = shape[0] *  shape[1]
            data = np.reshape(X[pointer:pointer+numberOfData],shape)
            retVal.append(data)
            pointer += numberOfData
        return retVal;
        
        
    def print_learningCurve(self):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
        _ = ax.plot(self.cost_function_values, label='cost function Werte');
        _ = ax.set_ylabel('cost function Werte')
        _ = ax.set_xlabel('Anzahl Generationen')
        _ = ax.set_title('Lern-Kurve')
        _ = ax.legend()
        return fig, ax

    def print_learningCurveStep(self):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
        _ = ax.plot(self.cost_function_values_step, label='cost function Werte');
        _ = ax.set_ylabel('cost function Werte')
        _ = ax.set_xlabel('Anzahl Schritte')

    def print_scoreCurve(self):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
        _ = ax.plot(self.score_values, label='score Werte');
        _ = ax.set_ylabel('score')
        _ = ax.set_xlabel('Generationen')
        _ = ax.set_title('Scores')
        _ = ax.legend()
        return fig, ax
    
    def score(self, X, y, method='accuracy'):
        return MultiLayerPerceptron.static_score(X,y,self.weights,self.layers)
    
    @staticmethod
    def static_score(X, y, weights, layers, method='accuracy'):
        if (y.ndim == 1 or y.shape[1] == 1):
            yPredicted = MultiLayerPerceptron.static_predict(X, weights, layers, False)
            yBool = y.astype(bool)
            yPredictedBool = yPredicted.astype(bool)
            TP = np.logical_and(yBool, yPredictedBool).sum()
            FP = np.logical_and(yBool == False, yPredictedBool).sum()

            TN = np.logical_and(yBool == False, yPredictedBool == False).sum()
            FN = np.logical_and(yBool, yPredictedBool == False).sum()

            PredictedT = yPredictedBool.sum()
            PredictedN = (yPredictedBool == False).sum()

            SampleT = yBool.sum()
            SampleN = (yBool == False).sum()

            Total = y.shape[0]
            #print('TP: {TP}, FP: {FP}, TN: {TN}, FN: {FN}'.format(TP=TP, FP=FP, TN=TN, FN=FN))

            if (method == 'accuracy'):
                return (TP + TN)/Total
            if (method == 'precision'):
                return TP / PredictedT
            if (method == 'recall'):
                return TP / SampleT
            if (method == 'f1'):
                prec = (TP / PredictedT)
                rec = (TP / SampleT)
                return 2*(prec * rec) / (prec + rec)
        
        predicted = MultiLayerPerceptron.static_predict(X, weights, layers, False)
        TP_TN = np.logical_and(y,predicted).sum()
        return (TP_TN) / len(y)
    
    def predict(self, X):
        return MultiLayerPerceptron.static_predict(X,weights=self.weights, layers=self.layers, verbose=False)
       
    
    @staticmethod
    def static_predict(X, weights, layers, verbose=False):
        vals = MultiLayerPerceptron.a(layer=layers, X=X, weights=weights, verbose=False).T
        
        if (vals.shape[1] == 1):
            vals = (vals >= 0.5).astype(int)
        else:
            vals = (vals == vals.max(axis=1)[:,None]).astype(int)
        return vals
    
    def confusion_matrix(self, X,y):
        predicted = self.predict(X).astype(int)
        real_y = np.atleast_2d(y.copy()).astype(int)
        if (real_y.shape[1] == 1):
            newFCol = []
            for newF in real_y:
                newFCol.append((newF == 0))
            real_y = np.column_stack((real_y, np.array(newFCol)))
            
            newFCol = []
            for newF in predicted:
                newFCol.append((newF == 0))
            
            predicted = np.column_stack((predicted, np.array(newFCol)))
        n_classes = real_y.shape[1]
        c_matrix = np.zeros((n_classes,n_classes))            
        
        for idx, ry in enumerate(real_y):
            c_matrix[np.argmax(predicted[idx])][np.argmax(ry)] += 1
        return c_matrix
    
    @staticmethod
    def plot_confusion_as_table(co_matrix):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,7))
        ax.axis('tight')
        ax.axis('off')

        #plt.show()
        tb = ax.table(cellText=co_matrix, 
               loc='center', 
               cellLoc='center',
               rowLoc='center',
               rowLabels=range(co_matrix.shape[0]), 
               colLabels=range(co_matrix.shape[1]))
        tb.set_fontsize(30)
        tb.scale(1,4)
        ax.set_title('confusion matrix')
        return fig, ax, tb
    
        
    def print_class_scores(self, X, y, method):
        yPredicted = self.predict(X)
        y_allBool = y.astype(bool)
        y_allPredictedBool = yPredicted.astype(bool)
        n_classes = 1
        if (y_allBool.ndim == 1):
            y_allBool = np.atleast_2d(y_allBool).T
        n_classes = y_allBool.shape[1]
        retVal = []
        for outputClass in range(n_classes):
            yBool = y_allBool.T[outputClass].T
            yPredictedBool = y_allPredictedBool.T[outputClass].T
            
            #print('evaluating output class: ', outputClass)
            TP = np.logical_and(yBool, yPredictedBool).sum()
            FP = np.logical_and(yBool == False, yPredictedBool).sum()

            TN = np.logical_and(yBool == False, yPredictedBool == False).sum()
            FN = np.logical_and(yBool, yPredictedBool == False).sum()

            PredictedT = yPredictedBool.sum()
            PredictedN = (yPredictedBool == False).sum()

            SampleT = yBool.sum()
            SampleN = (yBool == False).sum()

            Total = SampleT + SampleN
            #print('TP: {TP}, FP: {FP}, TN: {TN}, FN: {FN}, sampleT: {ST}, sampleN: {SN}'.format(TP=TP, FP=FP, TN=TN, FN=FN, ST=SampleT, SN=SampleN))
            
            if (method == 'accuracy'):
                acc = (TP + TN)/Total
                #print('acc:{ACC} TP: {TP}, FP: {FP}, TN: {TN}, FN: {FN}, sampleT: {ST}, sampleN: {SN}'.format(ACC=acc, TP=TP, FP=FP, TN=TN, FN=FN, ST=SampleT, SN=SampleN))
                retVal.append(acc)
            if (method == 'precision'):
                if (PredictedT == 0):
                    retVal.append(0)
                else:
                    retVal.append(TP / PredictedT)
            if (method == 'recall'):
                if (SampleT == 0):
                    retVal.append(0)
                else:
                    retVal.append(TP / SampleT)
            if (method == 'f1'):
                if ((SampleT == 0) or (PredictedT == 0)):
                    retVal.append(0)
                else:
                    prec = (TP / PredictedT)
                    rec = (TP / SampleT)
                    retVal.append(2*(prec * rec) / (prec + rec))
        return retVal

    print('++++++++++++++++++++ poly regularisiert ++++++++++++++++++++')

    ax.set_title('Lern-kurve poly overfitting')

    print_mlp_scores(mlp_poly, poly, devy, 'scores poly regularisierung:')

Mit undersampling reduzierie ich alle Klassen auf die Grsse der kleinsten Klasse, Dadurch werden extrem viele Informationen einfach weggeworfen, allerdings knnte das meinem Ansatz helfen.

def undersample():
    # find # of data to use class:
    n_data = int(trainy_mlp.sum(axis=0).min())

    #combine X & y to keep them togheter

    trainX_mlp2 = None
    trainy_mlp2 = None

    for c in range(trainy_mlp.shape[1]):
        allDataForThisClass = trainy_mlp[:,c]
        n_samples = int(allDataForThisClass.sum())

        relative_index = np.random.permutation(n_samples)[0:n_data]

        #print('n_samples {ns}, ind: {ind}'.format(ns=n_samples, ind=relative_index))
        counter = 0
        for idx, cv in enumerate(allDataForThisClass):
            if (cv == 1):
                if (counter in relative_index):
                    #add to train set
                    if (trainX_mlp2 is None):
                        trainX_mlp2 = np.array(trainX_mlp1[idx])
                        trainy_mlp2 = np.array(trainy_mlp[idx])
                    else:
                        trainX_mlp2 = np.vstack((trainX_mlp2, trainX_mlp1[idx]))
                        trainy_mlp2 = np.vstack((trainy_mlp2, trainy_mlp[idx]))
                counter += 1
    
    print('length should be #class * n_data\nexpected: {e}\ngot:{r}'.format(e=trainy_mlp.shape[1]*n_data, r=trainy_mlp2.shape[0]))
    return trainX_mlp2, trainy_mlp2

Oversampling¶

Beim Oversampling gibt es verschiedene Varianten. Eine der Varianten ist es, die minority-classes zu replizieren bis das Verhltnis aller Klassen = 1 ist. (Also einfach copy-paste) Ich werde diesen Ansatz in einem ersten Schritt verfolgen.

In [35]:
def oversample_1():
    # find # of data to use class:
    n_data = int(trainy_mlp.sum(axis=0).max())
    
    trainX_mlp3 = None
    trainy_mlp3 = None
    
    for c in range(trainy_mlp.shape[1]):
        allDataForThisClass = trainy_mlp[:,c]
        n_samples = int(allDataForThisClass.sum())

        n_duplicates = int(n_data/n_samples)
        n_rand_samples = n_data % n_samples
        relative_index = np.random.permutation(n_samples)[0:n_rand_samples]
        
        print('ns: ', n_samples, 'nd', n_duplicates,'rs',n_rand_samples)
        counter = 0
        for idx, cv in enumerate(allDataForThisClass):
            if (cv == 1):
                #add to train set
                if (trainX_mlp3 is None):
                    trainX_mlp3 = np.array(trainX_mlp1[idx])
                    trainy_mlp3 = np.array(trainy_mlp[idx])
                else:
                    trainX_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainX_mlp3, trainX_mlp1[idx]))
                    trainy_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainy_mlp3, trainy_mlp[idx]))

                if (n_duplicates > 1):
                    trainX_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainX_mlp3, [trainX_mlp1[idx]]*(n_duplicates -1)))
                    trainy_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainy_mlp3, [trainy_mlp[idx]]*(n_duplicates -1)))
                    
                    
                if (counter in relative_index):
                    trainX_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainX_mlp3, trainX_mlp1[idx]))
                    trainy_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainy_mlp3, trainy_mlp[idx]))
                counter += 1
#                 for z in range(n_duplicates - 1):
#                     trainX_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainX_mlp3, trainX_mlp1[idx]))
#                     trainy_mlp3 = np.vstack((trainy_mlp3, trainy_mlp[idx]))

    print('length should be #class * n_data\nexpected: {e}\ngot:{r}'.format(e=n_data*trainy_mlp.shape[1], r=trainy_mlp3.shape[0]))
    
    #shuffle output
    p = np.random.permutation(trainX_mlp3.shape[0])
    return trainX_mlp3[p], trainy_mlp3[p]

Schlusswort Multilayer Perceptron¶

Mit dem Multilayer Perceptron ist es mir gelungen die condition der Huser relativ gut bis perfekt vorauszusagen. Das Under und Oversampling fr die Datenaufbereitung hat sehr gut funktioniert und auch hier wieder, habe ich gemerkt, dass der Regularisierungs-Parameter $\lambda$ sehr wichtig fr das Resultat ist.

Mein Oversampling Ansatz ist eventuell etwas zu simpel gewhlt, weshalb hier immernoch kleine Fehler vorhanden sind. Bei meinem Ansatz ist es sehr schnell mglich Overfitting zu betreiben. Ich habe im Internet noch schlauere Anstze gefunden Daten zu generieren (Stichwort SMOTE), allerdings sind diese nicht simpel umzusetzen.

Ich habe ebenfalls noch interessante Anstze fr die datenpreparation gefunden (Tomek Link konkret), welche aber ebenfalls nicht einfach umzusetzen sind (Aufwand nach meinem Wissen O(n^2))
